Update the PATCH `/api/sessions/:id` route handler to `await` the now-async `updateSession()` call and catch permission mode rejections, returning 422.

## File to modify

### `apps/server/src/routes/sessions.ts` (lines 117-156)

The current PATCH handler calls `runtime.updateSession()` synchronously:
```typescript
const updated = runtime.updateSession(internalSessionId, {
  permissionMode,
  model,
  effort,
  fastMode,
  autoMode,
});
if (!updated) return sendError(res, 404, 'Session not found', 'SESSION_NOT_FOUND');
```

Change it to await and wrap in try/catch:
```typescript
try {
  const updated = await runtime.updateSession(internalSessionId, {
    permissionMode,
    model,
    effort,
    fastMode,
    autoMode,
  });
  if (!updated) return sendError(res, 404, 'Session not found', 'SESSION_NOT_FOUND');
} catch (err) {
  return res.status(422).json({
    error: 'Permission mode rejected by runtime',
    message: err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Unknown error',
  });
}
```

The `await` is safe because `boolean | Promise<boolean>` resolves immediately for synchronous returns and awaits properly for async returns.

The rest of the handler (fetching session, title rename, response) remains below the try/catch.

## Tests to add

Add to the sessions route test file (if one exists) or create integration-style tests:

```typescript
describe('PATCH /api/sessions/:id', () => {
  it('returns 422 when permission mode is rejected by runtime', async () => {
    // Mock runtime.updateSession to throw an error
    fakeRuntime.updateSession.mockRejectedValue(new Error('auto mode requires admin settings'));

    const res = await request(app)
      .patch('/api/sessions/test-session')
      .send({ permissionMode: 'auto' });

    expect(res.status).toBe(422);
    expect(res.body.error).toBe('Permission mode rejected by runtime');
    expect(res.body.message).toContain('auto mode requires admin settings');
  });

  it('returns 200 when permission mode update succeeds', async () => {
    fakeRuntime.updateSession.mockResolvedValue(true);
    fakeRuntime.getSession.mockResolvedValue({
      id: 'test-session',
      permissionMode: 'dontAsk',
      model: 'claude-sonnet',
    });

    const res = await request(app)
      .patch('/api/sessions/test-session')
      .send({ permissionMode: 'dontAsk' });

    expect(res.status).toBe(200);
  });
});
```

Note: The `FakeAgentRuntime.updateSession` mock type may need to change from `vi.fn<(...) => boolean>` to `vi.fn<(...) => boolean | Promise<boolean>>` to support `mockRejectedValue`. If this is needed, update it in `packages/test-utils/src/fake-agent-runtime.ts`:
```typescript
updateSession = vi.fn<
  (
    sessionId: string,
    opts: {
      permissionMode?: PermissionMode;
      model?: string;
      effort?: EffortLevel;
      fastMode?: boolean;
      autoMode?: boolean;
    }
  ) => boolean | Promise<boolean>
>(() => true);
```

## Acceptance criteria

- PATCH `/api/sessions/:id` with a permission mode that the SDK rejects returns HTTP 422
- The 422 response body contains `{ error: 'Permission mode rejected by runtime', message: '<SDK error>' }`
- Successful permission mode updates continue to return HTTP 200
- Non-permission-mode updates (model, effort, etc.) continue to work unchanged
- `pnpm typecheck` passes
- All existing and new tests pass

Expand the PermissionModeItem component to show all 6 modes, add a `supportedModes` prop for capability-based filtering, and apply warning styling to dangerous modes.

## File to modify

### `apps/client/src/layers/features/status/ui/PermissionModeItem.tsx`

Replace the entire file content with the following changes:

#### 1. Update imports — add Lock and Sparkles icons:
```typescript
import { Shield, ShieldCheck, ShieldOff, ClipboardList, Lock, Sparkles } from 'lucide-react';
```

#### 2. Expand PERMISSION_MODES array with `warn` field:
```typescript
const PERMISSION_MODES: {
  value: PermissionMode;
  label: string;
  icon: LucideIcon;
  description: string;
  warn?: boolean;
}[] = [
  { value: 'default', label: 'Default', icon: Shield, description: 'Prompt for each tool call' },
  {
    value: 'acceptEdits',
    label: 'Accept Edits',
    icon: ShieldCheck,
    description: 'Auto-approve file edits',
  },
  {
    value: 'plan',
    label: 'Plan Mode',
    icon: ClipboardList,
    description: 'Research only, no edits',
  },
  {
    value: 'dontAsk',
    label: "Don't Ask",
    icon: Lock,
    description: 'Only pre-approved tools run; everything else denied',
  },
  {
    value: 'bypassPermissions',
    label: 'Bypass All',
    icon: ShieldOff,
    description: 'Auto-approve everything',
    warn: true,
  },
  {
    value: 'auto',
    label: 'Auto',
    icon: Sparkles,
    description: 'AI classifier auto-approves actions',
    warn: true,
  },
];
```

Icon choices: `Lock` for `dontAsk` conveys lockdown/restrictive behavior; `Sparkles` for `auto` conveys AI/magic/automatic decision-making.

#### 3. Add `supportedModes` prop to the interface:
```typescript
interface PermissionModeItemProps {
  mode: PermissionMode;
  onChangeMode: (mode: PermissionMode) => void;
  /** When true, the selector is disabled and shows a tooltip explaining why. */
  disabled?: boolean;
  /** When provided, only modes in this array are shown in the dropdown. */
  supportedModes?: PermissionMode[];
}
```

#### 4. Update the component to filter by supported modes and use the `warn` field:
```typescript
export function PermissionModeItem({ mode, onChangeMode, disabled, supportedModes }: PermissionModeItemProps) {
  const availableModes = supportedModes
    ? PERMISSION_MODES.filter((m) => supportedModes.includes(m.value))
    : PERMISSION_MODES;

  // Fallback chain: find in available modes, then all modes, then first mode
  const current = availableModes.find((m) => m.value === mode)
    ?? PERMISSION_MODES.find((m) => m.value === mode)
    ?? PERMISSION_MODES[0];
  const Icon = current.icon;
  const isDangerous = current.warn === true;

  const trigger = (
    <button
      disabled={disabled}
      className={`hover:text-foreground inline-flex items-center gap-1 transition-colors duration-150 disabled:cursor-not-allowed disabled:opacity-40 ${isDangerous ? 'text-red-500' : ''}`}
    >
      <Icon className="size-(--size-icon-xs)" />
      <span>{current.label}</span>
    </button>
  );

  // ... disabled tooltip wrapper remains the same ...

  return (
    <ResponsiveDropdownMenu>
      <ResponsiveDropdownMenuTrigger asChild>{trigger}</ResponsiveDropdownMenuTrigger>
      <ResponsiveDropdownMenuContent side="top" align="start" className="w-56">
        <ResponsiveDropdownMenuLabel>Permission Mode</ResponsiveDropdownMenuLabel>
        <ResponsiveDropdownMenuRadioGroup
          value={mode}
          onValueChange={(v) => onChangeMode(v as PermissionMode)}
        >
          {availableModes.map((m) => (
            <ResponsiveDropdownMenuRadioItem
              key={m.value}
              value={m.value}
              icon={m.icon}
              description={m.description}
              className={m.warn ? 'text-red-500' : ''}
            >
              {m.label}
            </ResponsiveDropdownMenuRadioItem>
          ))}
        </ResponsiveDropdownMenuRadioGroup>
      </ResponsiveDropdownMenuContent>
    </ResponsiveDropdownMenu>
  );
}
```

Key changes from the old code:
- `isDangerous` now checks `current.warn === true` instead of `mode === 'bypassPermissions'`
- The dropdown iterates over `availableModes` instead of `PERMISSION_MODES`
- Each item uses `m.warn` for red styling instead of `m.value === 'bypassPermissions'`
- The fallback chain ensures the current mode always renders even if it's not in `supportedModes`

## Acceptance criteria

- All 6 modes render in the dropdown when no `supportedModes` prop is provided
- When `supportedModes={['default', 'plan']}` is provided, only those 2 modes show
- Both `bypassPermissions` and `auto` have red text styling in the dropdown
- `dontAsk` does NOT have red styling (it's restrictive, not dangerous)
- Current mode always displays in the trigger even if not in `supportedModes`
- `pnpm typecheck` passes

